3212/*
3213 * Pick up the highest-prio task:
3214 */
3215static inline struct task_struct *
3216pick_next_task(struct rq *rq, struct task_struct *prev, struct rq_flags *rf)
3217{
3218 const struct sched_class *class;
3219 struct task_struct *p;
3220
3221 /*
3222 * Optimization: we know that if all tasks are in the fair class we can
3223 * call that function directly, but only if the @prev task wasn't of a
3224 * higher scheduling class, because otherwise those loose the
3225 * opportunity to pull in more work from other CPUs.
3226 */
3227 if (likely((prev->sched_class == &idle_sched_class ||
3228 prev->sched_class == &fair_sched_class) &&
3229 rq->nr_running == rq->cfs.h_nr_running)) {
3230
3231 p = fair_sched_class.pick_next_task(rq, prev, rf);
3232 if (unlikely(p == RETRY_TASK))
3233 goto again;
3234
3235 /* Assumes fair_sched_class->next == idle_sched_class */
3236 if (unlikely(!p))
3237 p = idle_sched_class.pick_next_task(rq, prev, rf);
3238
3239 return p;
3240 }
3241
3242again:
3243 for_each_class(class) {
3244 p = class->pick_next_task(rq, prev, rf);
3245 if (p) {
3246 if (unlikely(p == RETRY_TASK))
3247 goto again;
3248 return p;
3249 }
3250 }
3251
3252 /* The idle class should always have a runnable task: */
3253 BUG();
3254}
3255
3256/*
3257 * __schedule() is the main scheduler function.
3258 *
3259 * The main means of driving the scheduler and thus entering this function are:
3260 *
3261 * 1. Explicit blocking: mutex, semaphore, waitqueue, etc.
3262 *
3263 * 2. TIF_NEED_RESCHED flag is checked on interrupt and userspace return
3264 * paths. For example, see arch/x86/entry_64.S.
3265 *
3266 * To drive preemption between tasks, the scheduler sets the flag in timer
3267 * interrupt handler scheduler_tick().
3268 *
3269 * 3. Wakeups don't really cause entry into schedule(). They add a
3270 * task to the run-queue and that's it.
3271 *
3272 * Now, if the new task added to the run-queue preempts the current
3273 * task, then the wakeup sets TIF_NEED_RESCHED and schedule() gets
3274 * called on the nearest possible occasion:
3275 *
3276 * - If the kernel is preemptible (CONFIG_PREEMPT=y):
3277 *
3278 * - in syscall or exception context, at the next outmost
3279 * preempt_enable(). (this might be as soon as the wake_up()'s
3280 * spin_unlock()!)
3281 *
3282 * - in IRQ context, return from interrupt-handler to
3283 * preemptible context
3284 *
3285 * - If the kernel is not preemptible (CONFIG_PREEMPT is not set)
3286 * then at the next:
3287 *
3288 * - cond_resched() call
3289 * - explicit schedule() call
3290 * - return from syscall or exception to user-space
3291 * - return from interrupt-handler to user-space
3292 *
3293 * WARNING: must be called with preemption disabled!
3294 */
3295static void __sched notrace __schedule(bool preempt)
3296{
3297 struct task_struct *prev, *next;
3298 unsigned long *switch_count;
3299 struct rq_flags rf;
3300 struct rq *rq;
3301 int cpu;
3302
3303 cpu = smp_processor_id();
3304 rq = cpu_rq(cpu);
3305 prev = rq->curr;
3306
3307 schedule_debug(prev);
3308
3309 if (sched_feat(HRTICK))
3310 hrtick_clear(rq);
3311
3312 local_irq_disable();
3313 rcu_note_context_switch(preempt);
3314
3315 /*
3316 * Make sure that signal_pending_state()->signal_pending() below
3317 * can't be reordered with __set_current_state(TASK_INTERRUPTIBLE)
3318 * done by the caller to avoid the race with signal_wake_up().
3319 */
3320 rq_lock(rq, &rf);
3321 smp_mb__after_spinlock();
3322
3323 /* Promote REQ to ACT */
3324 rq->clock_update_flags <<= 1;
3325 update_rq_clock(rq);
3326
3327 switch_count = &prev->nivcsw;
3328 if (!preempt && prev->state) {
3329 if (unlikely(signal_pending_state(prev->state, prev))) {
3330 prev->state = TASK_RUNNING;
3331 } else {
3332 deactivate_task(rq, prev, DEQUEUE_SLEEP | DEQUEUE_NOCLOCK);
3333 prev->on_rq = 0;
3334
3335 if (prev->in_iowait) {
3336 atomic_inc(&rq->nr_iowait);
3337 delayacct_blkio_start();
3338 }
3339
3340 /*
3341 * If a worker went to sleep, notify and ask workqueue
3342 * whether it wants to wake up a task to maintain
3343 * concurrency.
3344 */
3345 if (prev->flags & PF_WQ_WORKER) {
3346 struct task_struct *to_wakeup;
3347
3348 to_wakeup = wq_worker_sleeping(prev);
3349 if (to_wakeup)
3350 try_to_wake_up_local(to_wakeup, &rf);
3351 }
3352 }
3353 switch_count = &prev->nvcsw;
3354 }
3355
3356 next = pick_next_task(rq, prev, &rf);
3357 clear_tsk_need_resched(prev);
3358 clear_preempt_need_resched();
3359
3360 if (likely(prev != next)) {
3361 rq->nr_switches++;
3362 rq->curr = next;
3363 /*
3364 * The membarrier system call requires each architecture
3365 * to have a full memory barrier after updating
3366 * rq->curr, before returning to user-space. For TSO
3367 * (e.g. x86), the architecture must provide its own
3368 * barrier in switch_mm(). For weakly ordered machines
3369 * for which spin_unlock() acts as a full memory
3370 * barrier, finish_lock_switch() in common code takes
3371 * care of this barrier. For weakly ordered machines for
3372 * which spin_unlock() acts as a RELEASE barrier (only
3373 * arm64 and PowerPC), arm64 has a full barrier in
3374 * switch_to(), and PowerPC has
3375 * smp_mb__after_unlock_lock() before
3376 * finish_lock_switch().
3377 */
3378 ++*switch_count;
3379
3380 trace_sched_switch(preempt, prev, next);
3381
3382 /* Also unlocks the rq: */
3383 rq = context_switch(rq, prev, next, &rf);
3384 } else {
3385 rq->clock_update_flags &= ~(RQCF_ACT_SKIP|RQCF_REQ_SKIP);
3386 rq_unlock_irq(rq, &rf);
3387 }
3388
3389 balance_callback(rq);
3390}

3392void __noreturn do_task_dead(void)
3393{
3394 /* Causes final put_task_struct in finish_task_switch(): */
3395 set_special_state(TASK_DEAD);
3396
3397 /* Tell freezer to ignore us: */
3398 current->flags |= PF_NOFREEZE;
3399
3400 __schedule(false);
3401 BUG();
3402
3403 /* Avoid "noreturn function does return" - but don't continue if BUG() is a NOP: */
3404 for (;;)
3405 cpu_relax();
3406}

3408static inline void sched_submit_work(struct task_struct *tsk)
3409{
3410 if (!tsk->state || tsk_is_pi_blocked(tsk))
3411 return;
3412 /*
3413 * If we are going to sleep and we have plugged IO queued,
3414 * make sure to submit it to avoid deadlocks.
3415 */
3416 if (blk_needs_flush_plug(tsk))
3417 blk_schedule_flush_plug(tsk);
3418}

3420asmlinkage __visible void __sched schedule(void)
3421{
3422 struct task_struct *tsk = current;
3423
3424 sched_submit_work(tsk);
3425 do {
3426 preempt_disable();
3427 __schedule(false);
3428 sched_preempt_enable_no_resched();
3429 } while (need_resched());
3430}
3431EXPORT_SYMBOL(schedule);

3433/*
3434 * synchronize_rcu_tasks() makes sure that no task is stuck in preempted
3435 * state (have scheduled out non-voluntarily) by making sure that all
3436 * tasks have either left the run queue or have gone into user space.
3437 * As idle tasks do not do either, they must not ever be preempted
3438 * (schedule out non-voluntarily).
3439 *
3440 * schedule_idle() is similar to schedule_preempt_disable() except that it
3441 * never enables preemption because it does not call sched_submit_work().
3442 */
3443void __sched schedule_idle(void)
3444{
3445 /*
3446 * As this skips calling sched_submit_work(), which the idle task does
3447 * regardless because that function is a nop when the task is in a
3448 * TASK_RUNNING state, make sure this isn't used someplace that the
3449 * current task can be in any other state. Note, idle is always in the
3450 * TASK_RUNNING state.
3451 */
3452 WARN_ON_ONCE(current->state);
3453 do {
3454 __schedule(false);
3455 } while (need_resched());
3456}

3489static void __sched notrace preempt_schedule_common(void)
3490{
3491 do {
3492 /*
3493 * Because the function tracer can trace preempt_count_sub()
3494 * and it also uses preempt_enable/disable_notrace(), if
3495 * NEED_RESCHED is set, the preempt_enable_notrace() called
3496 * by the function tracer will call this function again and
3497 * cause infinite recursion.
3498 *
3499 * Preemption must be disabled here before the function
3500 * tracer can trace. Break up preempt_disable() into two
3501 * calls. One to disable preemption without fear of being
3502 * traced. The other to still record the preemption latency,
3503 * which can also be traced by the function tracer.
3504 */
3505 preempt_disable_notrace();
3506 preempt_latency_start(1);
3507 __schedule(true);
3508 preempt_latency_stop(1);
3509 preempt_enable_no_resched_notrace();
3510
3511 /*
3512 * Check again in case we missed a preemption opportunity
3513 * between schedule and now.
3514 */
3515 } while (need_resched());
3516}
3517
3518#ifdef CONFIG_PREEMPT
3519/*
3520 * this is the entry point to schedule() from in-kernel preemption
3521 * off of preempt_enable. Kernel preemptions off return from interrupt
3522 * occur there and call schedule directly.
3523 */
3524asmlinkage __visible void __sched notrace preempt_schedule(void)
3525{
3526 /*
3527 * If there is a non-zero preempt_count or interrupts are disabled,
3528 * we do not want to preempt the current task. Just return..
3529 */
3530 if (likely(!preemptible()))
3531 return;
3532
3533 preempt_schedule_common();
3534}
3535NOKPROBE_SYMBOL(preempt_schedule);
3536EXPORT_SYMBOL(preempt_schedule);
3537
3538/**
3539 * preempt_schedule_notrace - preempt_schedule called by tracing
3540 *
3541 * The tracing infrastructure uses preempt_enable_notrace to prevent
3542 * recursion and tracing preempt enabling caused by the tracing
3543 * infrastructure itself. But as tracing can happen in areas coming
3544 * from userspace or just about to enter userspace, a preempt enable
3545 * can occur before user_exit() is called. This will cause the scheduler
3546 * to be called when the system is still in usermode.
3547 *
3548 * To prevent this, the preempt_enable_notrace will use this function
3549 * instead of preempt_schedule() to exit user context if needed before
3550 * calling the scheduler.
3551 */
3552asmlinkage __visible void __sched notrace preempt_schedule_notrace(void)
3553{
3554 enum ctx_state prev_ctx;
3555
3556 if (likely(!preemptible()))
3557 return;
3558
3559 do {
3560 /*
3561 * Because the function tracer can trace preempt_count_sub()
3562 * and it also uses preempt_enable/disable_notrace(), if
3563 * NEED_RESCHED is set, the preempt_enable_notrace() called
3564 * by the function tracer will call this function again and
3565 * cause infinite recursion.
3566 *
3567 * Preemption must be disabled here before the function
3568 * tracer can trace. Break up preempt_disable() into two
3569 * calls. One to disable preemption without fear of being
3570 * traced. The other to still record the preemption latency,
3571 * which can also be traced by the function tracer.
3572 */
3573 preempt_disable_notrace();
3574 preempt_latency_start(1);
3575 /*
3576 * Needs preempt disabled in case user_exit() is traced
3577 * and the tracer calls preempt_enable_notrace() causing
3578 * an infinite recursion.
3579 */
3580 prev_ctx = exception_enter();
3581 __schedule(true);
3582 exception_exit(prev_ctx);
3583
3584 preempt_latency_stop(1);
3585 preempt_enable_no_resched_notrace();
3586 } while (need_resched());
3587}
3588EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(preempt_schedule_notrace);
3589
3590#endif /* CONFIG_PREEMPT */
3591
3592/*
3593 * this is the entry point to schedule() from kernel preemption
3594 * off of irq context.
3595 * Note, that this is called and return with irqs disabled. This will
3596 * protect us against recursive calling from irq.
3597 */
3598asmlinkage __visible void __sched preempt_schedule_irq(void)
3599{
3600 enum ctx_state prev_state;
3601
3602 /* Catch callers which need to be fixed */
3603 BUG_ON(preempt_count() || !irqs_disabled());
3604
3605 prev_state = exception_enter();
3606
3607 do {
3608 preempt_disable();
3609 local_irq_enable();
3610 __schedule(true);
3611 local_irq_disable();
3612 sched_preempt_enable_no_resched();
3613 } while (need_resched());
3614
3615 exception_exit(prev_state);
3616}

3642/*
3643 * rt_mutex_setprio - set the current priority of a task
3644 * @p: task to boost
3645 * @pi_task: donor task
3646 *
3647 * This function changes the 'effective' priority of a task. It does
3648 * not touch ->normal_prio like __setscheduler().
3649 *
3650 * Used by the rt_mutex code to implement priority inheritance
3651 * logic. Call site only calls if the priority of the task changed.
3652 */
3653void rt_mutex_setprio(struct task_struct *p, struct task_struct *pi_task)
3654{
3655 int prio, oldprio, queued, running, queue_flag =
3656 DEQUEUE_SAVE | DEQUEUE_MOVE | DEQUEUE_NOCLOCK;
3657 const struct sched_class *prev_class;
3658 struct rq_flags rf;
3659 struct rq *rq;
3660
3661 /* XXX used to be waiter->prio, not waiter->task->prio */
3662 prio = __rt_effective_prio(pi_task, p->normal_prio);
3663
3664 /*
3665 * If nothing changed; bail early.
3666 */
3667 if (p->pi_top_task == pi_task && prio == p->prio && !dl_prio(prio))
3668 return;
3669
3670 rq = __task_rq_lock(p, &rf);
3671 update_rq_clock(rq);
3672 /*
3673 * Set under pi_lock && rq->lock, such that the value can be used under
3674 * either lock.
3675 *
3676 * Note that there is loads of tricky to make this pointer cache work
3677 * right. rt_mutex_slowunlock()+rt_mutex_postunlock() work together to
3678 * ensure a task is de-boosted (pi_task is set to NULL) before the
3679 * task is allowed to run again (and can exit). This ensures the pointer
3680 * points to a blocked task -- which guaratees the task is present.
3681 */
3682 p->pi_top_task = pi_task;
3683
3684 /*
3685 * For FIFO/RR we only need to set prio, if that matches we're done.
3686 */
3687 if (prio == p->prio && !dl_prio(prio))
3688 goto out_unlock;
3689
3690 /*
3691 * Idle task boosting is a nono in general. There is one
3692 * exception, when PREEMPT_RT and NOHZ is active:
3693 *
3694 * The idle task calls get_next_timer_interrupt() and holds
3695 * the timer wheel base->lock on the CPU and another CPU wants
3696 * to access the timer (probably to cancel it). We can safely
3697 * ignore the boosting request, as the idle CPU runs this code
3698 * with interrupts disabled and will complete the lock
3699 * protected section without being interrupted. So there is no
3700 * real need to boost.
3701 */
3702 if (unlikely(p == rq->idle)) {
3703 WARN_ON(p != rq->curr);
3704 WARN_ON(p->pi_blocked_on);
3705 goto out_unlock;
3706 }
3707
3708 trace_sched_pi_setprio(p, pi_task);
3709 oldprio = p->prio;
3710
3711 if (oldprio == prio)
3712 queue_flag &= ~DEQUEUE_MOVE;
3713
3714 prev_class = p->sched_class;
3715 queued = task_on_rq_queued(p);
3716 running = task_current(rq, p);
3717 if (queued)
3718 dequeue_task(rq, p, queue_flag);
3719 if (running)
3720 put_prev_task(rq, p);
3721
3722 /*
3723 * Boosting condition are:
3724 * 1. -rt task is running and holds mutex A
3725 * --> -dl task blocks on mutex A
3726 *
3727 * 2. -dl task is running and holds mutex A
3728 * --> -dl task blocks on mutex A and could preempt the
3729 * running task
3730 */
3731 if (dl_prio(prio)) {
3732 if (!dl_prio(p->normal_prio) ||
3733 (pi_task && dl_entity_preempt(&pi_task->dl, &p->dl))) {
3734 p->dl.dl_boosted = 1;
3735 queue_flag |= ENQUEUE_REPLENISH;
3736 } else
3737 p->dl.dl_boosted = 0;
3738 p->sched_class = &dl_sched_class;
3739 } else if (rt_prio(prio)) {
3740 if (dl_prio(oldprio))
3741 p->dl.dl_boosted = 0;
3742 if (oldprio < prio)
3743 queue_flag |= ENQUEUE_HEAD;
3744 p->sched_class = &rt_sched_class;
3745 } else {
3746 if (dl_prio(oldprio))
3747 p->dl.dl_boosted = 0;
3748 if (rt_prio(oldprio))
3749 p->rt.timeout = 0;
3750 p->sched_class = &fair_sched_class;
3751 }
3752
3753 p->prio = prio;
3754
3755 if (queued)
3756 enqueue_task(rq, p, queue_flag);
3757 if (running)
3758 set_curr_task(rq, p);
3759
3760 check_class_changed(rq, p, prev_class, oldprio);
3761out_unlock:
3762 /* Avoid rq from going away on us: */
3763 preempt_disable();
3764 __task_rq_unlock(rq, &rf);
3765
3766 balance_callback(rq);
3767 preempt_enable();
3768}
3769#else
3770static inline int rt_effective_prio(struct task_struct *p, int prio)
3771{
3772 return prio;
3773}
3774#endif
3775
3776void set_user_nice(struct task_struct *p, long nice)
3777{
3778 bool queued, running;
3779 int old_prio, delta;
3780 struct rq_flags rf;
3781 struct rq *rq;
3782
3783 if (task_nice(p) == nice || nice < MIN_NICE || nice > MAX_NICE)
3784 return;
3785 /*
3786 * We have to be careful, if called from sys_setpriority(),
3787 * the task might be in the middle of scheduling on another CPU.
3788 */
3789 rq = task_rq_lock(p, &rf);
3790 update_rq_clock(rq);
3791
3792 /*
3793 * The RT priorities are set via sched_setscheduler(), but we still
3794 * allow the 'normal' nice value to be set - but as expected
3795 * it wont have any effect on scheduling until the task is
3796 * SCHED_DEADLINE, SCHED_FIFO or SCHED_RR:
3797 */
3798 if (task_has_dl_policy(p) || task_has_rt_policy(p)) {
3799 p->static_prio = NICE_TO_PRIO(nice);
3800 goto out_unlock;
3801 }
3802 queued = task_on_rq_queued(p);
3803 running = task_current(rq, p);
3804 if (queued)
3805 dequeue_task(rq, p, DEQUEUE_SAVE | DEQUEUE_NOCLOCK);
3806 if (running)
3807 put_prev_task(rq, p);
3808
3809 p->static_prio = NICE_TO_PRIO(nice);
3810 set_load_weight(p);
3811 old_prio = p->prio;
3812 p->prio = effective_prio(p);
3813 delta = p->prio - old_prio;
3814
3815 if (queued) {
3816 enqueue_task(rq, p, ENQUEUE_RESTORE | ENQUEUE_NOCLOCK);
3817 /*
3818 * If the task increased its priority or is running and
3819 * lowered its priority, then reschedule its CPU:
3820 */
3821 if (delta < 0 || (delta > 0 && task_running(rq, p)))
3822 resched_curr(rq);
3823 }
3824 if (running)
3825 set_curr_task(rq, p);
3826out_unlock:
3827 task_rq_unlock(rq, p, &rf);
3828}
3829EXPORT_SYMBOL(set_user_nice);

3831/*
3832 * can_nice - check if a task can reduce its nice value
3833 * @p: task
3834 * @nice: nice value
3835 */
3836int can_nice(const struct task_struct *p, const int nice)
3837{
3838 /* Convert nice value [19,-20] to rlimit style value [1,40]: */
3839 int nice_rlim = nice_to_rlimit(nice);
3840
3841 return (nice_rlim <= task_rlimit(p, RLIMIT_NICE) ||
3842 capable(CAP_SYS_NICE));
3843}

3847/*
3848 * sys_nice - change the priority of the current process.
3849 * @increment: priority increment
3850 *
3851 * sys_setpriority is a more generic, but much slower function that
3852 * does similar things.
3853 */
3854SYSCALL_DEFINE1(nice, int, increment)
3855{
3856 long nice, retval;
3857
3858 /*
3859 * Setpriority might change our priority at the same moment.
3860 * We don't have to worry. Conceptually one call occurs first
3861 * and we have a single winner.
3862 */
3863 increment = clamp(increment, -NICE_WIDTH, NICE_WIDTH);
3864 nice = task_nice(current) + increment;
3865
3866 nice = clamp_val(nice, MIN_NICE, MAX_NICE);
3867 if (increment < 0 && !can_nice(current, nice))
3868 return -EPERM;
3869
3870 retval = security_task_setnice(current, nice);
3871 if (retval)
3872 return retval;
3873
3874 set_user_nice(current, nice);
3875 return 0;
3876}

3939/*
3940 * sched_setparam() passes in -1 for its policy, to let the functions
3941 * it calls know not to change it.
3942 */
3943#define SETPARAM_POLICY -1
3944
3945static void __setscheduler_params(struct task_struct *p,
3946 const struct sched_attr *attr)
3947{
3948 int policy = attr->sched_policy;
3949
3950 if (policy == SETPARAM_POLICY)
3951 policy = p->policy;
3952
3953 p->policy = policy;
3954
3955 if (dl_policy(policy))
3956 __setparam_dl(p, attr);
3957 else if (fair_policy(policy))
3958 p->static_prio = NICE_TO_PRIO(attr->sched_nice);
3959
3960 /*
3961 * __sched_setscheduler() ensures attr->sched_priority == 0 when
3962 * !rt_policy. Always setting this ensures that things like
3963 * getparam()/getattr() don't report silly values for !rt tasks.
3964 */
3965 p->rt_priority = attr->sched_priority;
3966 p->normal_prio = normal_prio(p);
3967 set_load_weight(p);
3968}
3969
3970/* Actually do priority change: must hold pi & rq lock. */
3971static void __setscheduler(struct rq *rq, struct task_struct *p,
3972 const struct sched_attr *attr, bool keep_boost)
3973{
3974 __setscheduler_params(p, attr);
3975
3976 /*
3977 * Keep a potential priority boosting if called from
3978 * sched_setscheduler().
3979 */
3980 p->prio = normal_prio(p);
3981 if (keep_boost)
3982 p->prio = rt_effective_prio(p, p->prio);
3983
3984 if (dl_prio(p->prio))
3985 p->sched_class = &dl_sched_class;
3986 else if (rt_prio(p->prio))
3987 p->sched_class = &rt_sched_class;
3988 else
3989 p->sched_class = &fair_sched_class;
3990}

3993 * Check the target process has a UID that matches the current process's:
3994 */
3995static bool check_same_owner(struct task_struct *p)
3996{
3997 const struct cred *cred = current_cred(), *pcred;
3998 bool match;
3999
4000 rcu_read_lock();
4001 pcred = __task_cred(p);
4002 match = (uid_eq(cred->euid, pcred->euid) ||
4003 uid_eq(cred->euid, pcred->uid));

4007
4008static int __sched_setscheduler(struct task_struct *p,
4009 const struct sched_attr *attr,
4010 bool user, bool pi)
4011{
4012 int newprio = dl_policy(attr->sched_policy) ? MAX_DL_PRIO - 1 :
4013 MAX_RT_PRIO - 1 - attr->sched_priority;
4014 int retval, oldprio, oldpolicy = -1, queued, running;
4015 int new_effective_prio, policy = attr->sched_policy;
4016 const struct sched_class *prev_class;
4017 struct rq_flags rf;
4018 int reset_on_fork;
4019 int queue_flags = DEQUEUE_SAVE | DEQUEUE_MOVE | DEQUEUE_NOCLOCK;
4020 struct rq *rq;
4021
4022 /* The pi code expects interrupts enabled */
4023 BUG_ON(pi && in_interrupt());
4024recheck:
4025 /* Double check policy once rq lock held: */
4026 if (policy < 0) {
4027 reset_on_fork = p->sched_reset_on_fork;
4028 policy = oldpolicy = p->policy;
4029 } else {
4030 reset_on_fork = !!(attr->sched_flags & SCHED_FLAG_RESET_ON_FORK);
4031
4032 if (!valid_policy(policy))
4033 return -EINVAL;
4034 }
4035
4036 if (attr->sched_flags &
4037 ~(SCHED_FLAG_RESET_ON_FORK | SCHED_FLAG_RECLAIM))
4038 return -EINVAL;
4039
4040 /*
4041 * Valid priorities for SCHED_FIFO and SCHED_RR are
4042 * 1..MAX_USER_RT_PRIO-1, valid priority for SCHED_NORMAL,
4043 * SCHED_BATCH and SCHED_IDLE is 0.
4044 */
4045 if ((p->mm && attr->sched_priority > MAX_USER_RT_PRIO-1) ||
4046 (!p->mm && attr->sched_priority > MAX_RT_PRIO-1))
4047 return -EINVAL;
4048 if ((dl_policy(policy) && !__checkparam_dl(attr)) ||
4049 (rt_policy(policy) != (attr->sched_priority != 0)))
4050 return -EINVAL;
4051
4052 /*
4053 * Allow unprivileged RT tasks to decrease priority:
4054 */
4055 if (user && !capable(CAP_SYS_NICE)) {
4056 if (fair_policy(policy)) {
4057 if (attr->sched_nice < task_nice(p) &&
4058 !can_nice(p, attr->sched_nice))
4059 return -EPERM;
4060 }
4061
4062 if (rt_policy(policy)) {
4063 unsigned long rlim_rtprio =
4064 task_rlimit(p, RLIMIT_RTPRIO);
4065
4066 /* Can't set/change the rt policy: */
4067 if (policy != p->policy && !rlim_rtprio)
4068 return -EPERM;
4069
4070 /* Can't increase priority: */
4071 if (attr->sched_priority > p->rt_priority &&
4072 attr->sched_priority > rlim_rtprio)
4073 return -EPERM;
4074 }
4075
4076 /*
4077 * Can't set/change SCHED_DEADLINE policy at all for now
4078 * (safest behavior); in the future we would like to allow
4079 * unprivileged DL tasks to increase their relative deadline
4080 * or reduce their runtime (both ways reducing utilization)
4081 */
4082 if (dl_policy(policy))
4083 return -EPERM;
4084
4085 /*
4086 * Treat SCHED_IDLE as nice 20. Only allow a switch to
4087 * SCHED_NORMAL if the RLIMIT_NICE would normally permit it.
4088 */
4089 if (idle_policy(p->policy) && !idle_policy(policy)) {
4090 if (!can_nice(p, task_nice(p)))
4091 return -EPERM;
4092 }
4093
4094 /* Can't change other user's priorities: */
4095 if (!check_same_owner(p))
4096 return -EPERM;
4097
4098 /* Normal users shall not reset the sched_reset_on_fork flag: */
4099 if (p->sched_reset_on_fork && !reset_on_fork)
4100 return -EPERM;
4101 }
4102
4103 if (user) {
4104 retval = security_task_setscheduler(p);
4105 if (retval)
4106 return retval;
4107 }
4108
4109 /*
4110 * Make sure no PI-waiters arrive (or leave) while we are
4111 * changing the priority of the task:
4112 *
4113 * To be able to change p->policy safely, the appropriate
4114 * runqueue lock must be held.
4115 */
4116 rq = task_rq_lock(p, &rf);
4117 update_rq_clock(rq);
4118
4119 /*
4120 * Changing the policy of the stop threads its a very bad idea:
4121 */
4122 if (p == rq->stop) {
4123 task_rq_unlock(rq, p, &rf);
4124 return -EINVAL;
4125 }
4126
4127 /*
4128 * If not changing anything there's no need to proceed further,
4129 * but store a possible modification of reset_on_fork.
4130 */
4131 if (unlikely(policy == p->policy)) {
4132 if (fair_policy(policy) && attr->sched_nice != task_nice(p))
4133 goto change;
4134 if (rt_policy(policy) && attr->sched_priority != p->rt_priority)
4135 goto change;
4136 if (dl_policy(policy) && dl_param_changed(p, attr))
4137 goto change;
4138
4139 p->sched_reset_on_fork = reset_on_fork;
4140 task_rq_unlock(rq, p, &rf);
4141 return 0;
4142 }
4143change:
4144
4145 if (user) {
4146#ifdef CONFIG_RT_GROUP_SCHED
4147 /*
4148 * Do not allow realtime tasks into groups that have no runtime
4149 * assigned.
4150 */
4151 if (rt_bandwidth_enabled() && rt_policy(policy) &&
4152 task_group(p)->rt_bandwidth.rt_runtime == 0 &&
4153 !task_group_is_autogroup(task_group(p))) {
4154 task_rq_unlock(rq, p, &rf);
4155 return -EPERM;
4156 }
4157#endif
4158#ifdef CONFIG_SMP
4159 if (dl_bandwidth_enabled() && dl_policy(policy)) {
4160 cpumask_t *span = rq->rd->span;
4161
4162 /*
4163 * Don't allow tasks with an affinity mask smaller than
4164 * the entire root_domain to become SCHED_DEADLINE. We
4165 * will also fail if there's no bandwidth available.
4166 */
4167 if (!cpumask_subset(span, &p->cpus_allowed) ||
4168 rq->rd->dl_bw.bw == 0) {
4169 task_rq_unlock(rq, p, &rf);
4170 return -EPERM;
4171 }
4172 }
4173#endif
4174 }
4175
4176 /* Re-check policy now with rq lock held: */
4177 if (unlikely(oldpolicy != -1 && oldpolicy != p->policy)) {
4178 policy = oldpolicy = -1;
4179 task_rq_unlock(rq, p, &rf);
4180 goto recheck;
4181 }
4182
4183 /*
4184 * If setscheduling to SCHED_DEADLINE (or changing the parameters
4185 * of a SCHED_DEADLINE task) we need to check if enough bandwidth
4186 * is available.
4187 */
4188 if ((dl_policy(policy) || dl_task(p)) && sched_dl_overflow(p, policy, attr)) {
4189 task_rq_unlock(rq, p, &rf);
4190 return -EBUSY;
4191 }
4192
4193 p->sched_reset_on_fork = reset_on_fork;
4194 oldprio = p->prio;
4195
4196 if (pi) {
4197 /*
4198 * Take priority boosted tasks into account. If the new
4199 * effective priority is unchanged, we just store the new
4200 * normal parameters and do not touch the scheduler class and
4201 * the runqueue. This will be done when the task deboost
4202 * itself.
4203 */
4204 new_effective_prio = rt_effective_prio(p, newprio);
4205 if (new_effective_prio == oldprio)
4206 queue_flags &= ~DEQUEUE_MOVE;
4207 }
4208
4209 queued = task_on_rq_queued(p);
4210 running = task_current(rq, p);
4211 if (queued)
4212 dequeue_task(rq, p, queue_flags);
4213 if (running)
4214 put_prev_task(rq, p);
4215
4216 prev_class = p->sched_class;
4217 __setscheduler(rq, p, attr, pi);
4218
4219 if (queued) {
4220 /*
4221 * We enqueue to tail when the priority of a task is
4222 * increased (user space view).
4223 */
4224 if (oldprio < p->prio)
4225 queue_flags |= ENQUEUE_HEAD;
4226
4227 enqueue_task(rq, p, queue_flags);
4228 }
4229 if (running)
4230 set_curr_task(rq, p);
4231
4232 check_class_changed(rq, p, prev_class, oldprio);
4233
4234 /* Avoid rq from going away on us: */
4235 preempt_disable();
4236 task_rq_unlock(rq, p, &rf);
4237
4238 if (pi)
4239 rt_mutex_adjust_pi(p);
4240
4241 /* Run balance callbacks after we've adjusted the PI chain: */
4242 balance_callback(rq);
4243 preempt_enable();
4244
4245 return 0;
4246}

4248static int _sched_setscheduler(struct task_struct *p, int policy,
4249 const struct sched_param *param, bool check)
4250{
4251 struct sched_attr attr = {
4252 .sched_policy = policy,
4253 .sched_priority = param->sched_priority,
4254 .sched_nice = PRIO_TO_NICE(p->static_prio),
4255 };
4256
4257 /* Fixup the legacy SCHED_RESET_ON_FORK hack. */
4258 if ((policy != SETPARAM_POLICY) && (policy & SCHED_RESET_ON_FORK)) {
4259 attr.sched_flags |= SCHED_FLAG_RESET_ON_FORK;
4260 policy &= ~SCHED_RESET_ON_FORK;
4261 attr.sched_policy = policy;
4262 }
4263
4264 return __sched_setscheduler(p, &attr, check, true);
4265}

4274 * NOTE that the task may be already dead.

4276int sched_setscheduler(struct task_struct *p, int policy,

4278{

4331/*
4332 * Mimics kernel/events/core.c perf_copy_attr().
4333 */
4334static int sched_copy_attr(struct sched_attr __user *uattr, struct sched_attr *attr)
4335{
4336 u32 size;
4337 int ret;
4338
4339 if (!access_ok(VERIFY_WRITE, uattr, SCHED_ATTR_SIZE_VER0))
4340 return -EFAULT;
4341
4342 /* Zero the full structure, so that a short copy will be nice: */
4343 memset(attr, 0, sizeof(*attr));
4344
4345 ret = get_user(size, &uattr->size);
4346 if (ret)
4347 return ret;
4348
4349 /* Bail out on silly large: */
4350 if (size > PAGE_SIZE)
4351 goto err_size;
4352
4353 /* ABI compatibility quirk: */
4354 if (!size)
4355 size = SCHED_ATTR_SIZE_VER0;
4356
4357 if (size < SCHED_ATTR_SIZE_VER0)
4358 goto err_size;
4359
4360 /*
4361 * If we're handed a bigger struct than we know of,
4362 * ensure all the unknown bits are 0 - i.e. new
4363 * user-space does not rely on any kernel feature
4364 * extensions we dont know about yet.
4365 */
4366 if (size > sizeof(*attr)) {
4367 unsigned char __user *addr;
4368 unsigned char __user *end;
4369 unsigned char val;
4370
4371 addr = (void __user *)uattr + sizeof(*attr);
4372 end = (void __user *)uattr + size;
4373
4374 for (; addr < end; addr++) {
4375 ret = get_user(val, addr);
4376 if (ret)
4377 return ret;
4378 if (val)
4379 goto err_size;
4380 }
4381 size = sizeof(*attr);
4382 }
4383
4384 ret = copy_from_user(attr, uattr, size);
4385 if (ret)
4386 return -EFAULT;
4387
4388 /*
4389 * XXX: Do we want to be lenient like existing syscalls; or do we want
4390 * to be strict and return an error on out-of-bounds values?
4391 */
4392 attr->sched_nice = clamp(attr->sched_nice, MIN_NICE, MAX_NICE);
4393
4394 return 0;
4395
4396err_size:
4397 put_user(sizeof(*attr), &uattr->size);
4398 return -E2BIG;
4399}

4533static int sched_read_attr(struct sched_attr __user *uattr,
4534 struct sched_attr *attr,
4535 unsigned int usize)
4536{
4537 int ret;
4538
4539 if (!access_ok(VERIFY_WRITE, uattr, usize))
4540 return -EFAULT;
4541
4542 /*
4543 * If we're handed a smaller struct than we know of,
4544 * ensure all the unknown bits are 0 - i.e. old
4545 * user-space does not get uncomplete information.
4546 */
4547 if (usize < sizeof(*attr)) {
4548 unsigned char *addr;
4549 unsigned char *end;
4550
4551 addr = (void *)attr + usize;
4552 end = (void *)attr + sizeof(*attr);
4553
4554 for (; addr < end; addr++) {
4555 if (*addr)
4556 return -EFBIG;
4557 }
4558
4559 attr->size = usize;
4560 }
4561
4562 ret = copy_to_user(uattr, attr, attr->size);
4563 if (ret)
4564 return -EFAULT;
4565
4566 return 0;
4567}

4569/**
4570 * sys_sched_getattr - similar to sched_getparam, but with sched_attr
4571 * @pid: the pid in question.
4572 * @uattr: structure containing the extended parameters.
4573 * @size: sizeof(attr) for fwd/bwd comp.
4574 * @flags: for future extension.
4575 */
4576SYSCALL_DEFINE4(sched_getattr, pid_t, pid, struct sched_attr __user *, uattr,
4577 unsigned int, size, unsigned int, flags)
4578{
4579 struct sched_attr attr = {
4580 .size = sizeof(struct sched_attr),
4581 };
4582 struct task_struct *p;
4583 int retval;
4584
4585 if (!uattr || pid < 0 || size > PAGE_SIZE ||
4586 size < SCHED_ATTR_SIZE_VER0 || flags)
4587 return -EINVAL;
4588
4589 rcu_read_lock();
4590 p = find_process_by_pid(pid);
4591 retval = -ESRCH;
4592 if (!p)
4593 goto out_unlock;
4594
4595 retval = security_task_getscheduler(p);
4596 if (retval)
4597 goto out_unlock;
4598
4599 attr.sched_policy = p->policy;
4600 if (p->sched_reset_on_fork)
4601 attr.sched_flags |= SCHED_FLAG_RESET_ON_FORK;
4602 if (task_has_dl_policy(p))
4603 __getparam_dl(p, &attr);
4604 else if (task_has_rt_policy(p))
4605 attr.sched_priority = p->rt_priority;
4606 else
4607 attr.sched_nice = task_nice(p);
4608
4609 rcu_read_unlock();
4610
4611 retval = sched_read_attr(uattr, &attr, size);
4612 return retval;
4613
4614out_unlock:

4616 return retval;

4618
4619long sched_setaffinity(pid_t pid, const struct cpumask *in_mask)
4620{
4621 cpumask_var_t cpus_allowed, new_mask;
4622 struct task_struct *p;
4623 int retval;
4624
4625 rcu_read_lock();
4626
4627 p = find_process_by_pid(pid);
4628 if (!p) {
4629 rcu_read_unlock();
4630 return -ESRCH;
4631 }
4632
4633 /* Prevent p going away */
4634 get_task_struct(p);
4635 rcu_read_unlock();
4636
4637 if (p->flags & PF_NO_SETAFFINITY) {
4638 retval = -EINVAL;
4639 goto out_put_task;
4640 }
4641 if (!alloc_cpumask_var(&cpus_allowed, GFP_KERNEL)) {
4642 retval = -ENOMEM;
4643 goto out_put_task;
4644 }
4645 if (!alloc_cpumask_var(&new_mask, GFP_KERNEL)) {
4646 retval = -ENOMEM;
4647 goto out_free_cpus_allowed;
4648 }
4649 retval = -EPERM;
4650 if (!check_same_owner(p)) {
4651 rcu_read_lock();
4652 if (!ns_capable(__task_cred(p)->user_ns, CAP_SYS_NICE)) {
4653 rcu_read_unlock();
4654 goto out_free_new_mask;
4655 }
4656 rcu_read_unlock();
4657 }
4658
4659 retval = security_task_setscheduler(p);
4660 if (retval)
4661 goto out_free_new_mask;
4662
4663
4664 cpuset_cpus_allowed(p, cpus_allowed);
4665 cpumask_and(new_mask, in_mask, cpus_allowed);
4666
4667 /*
4668 * Since bandwidth control happens on root_domain basis,
4669 * if admission test is enabled, we only admit -deadline
4670 * tasks allowed to run on all the CPUs in the task's
4671 * root_domain.
4672 */
4673#ifdef CONFIG_SMP
4674 if (task_has_dl_policy(p) && dl_bandwidth_enabled()) {
4675 rcu_read_lock();
4676 if (!cpumask_subset(task_rq(p)->rd->span, new_mask)) {
4677 retval = -EBUSY;
4678 rcu_read_unlock();
4679 goto out_free_new_mask;
4680 }
4681 rcu_read_unlock();
4682 }
4683#endif
4684again:
4685 retval = __set_cpus_allowed_ptr(p, new_mask, true);
4686
4687 if (!retval) {
4688 cpuset_cpus_allowed(p, cpus_allowed);
4689 if (!cpumask_subset(new_mask, cpus_allowed)) {
4690 /*
4691 * We must have raced with a concurrent cpuset
4692 * update. Just reset the cpus_allowed to the
4693 * cpuset's cpus_allowed
4694 */
4695 cpumask_copy(new_mask, cpus_allowed);
4696 goto again;
4697 }
4698 }
4699out_free_new_mask:
4700 free_cpumask_var(new_mask);
4701out_free_cpus_allowed:
4702 free_cpumask_var(cpus_allowed);
4703out_put_task:
4704 put_task_struct(p);
4705 return retval;
4706}

4708static int get_user_cpu_mask(unsigned long __user *user_mask_ptr, unsigned len,
4709 struct cpumask *new_mask)
4710{
4711 if (len < cpumask_size())
4712 cpumask_clear(new_mask);
4713 else if (len > cpumask_size())
4714 len = cpumask_size();
4715
4716 return copy_from_user(new_mask, user_mask_ptr, len) ? -EFAULT : 0;
4717}

4719/**
4720 * sys_sched_setaffinity - set the CPU affinity of a process
4721 * @pid: pid of the process
4722 * @len: length in bytes of the bitmask pointed to by user_mask_ptr
4723 * @user_mask_ptr: user-space pointer to the new CPU mask
4724 *
4725 * Return: 0 on success. An error code otherwise.
4726 */
4727SYSCALL_DEFINE3(sched_setaffinity, pid_t, pid, unsigned int, len,
4728 unsigned long __user *, user_mask_ptr)
4729{
4730 cpumask_var_t new_mask;
4731 int retval;

4743long sched_getaffinity(pid_t pid, struct cpumask *mask)
4744{
4745 struct task_struct *p;
4746 unsigned long flags;
4747 int retval;
4748
4749 rcu_read_lock();
4750
4751 retval = -ESRCH;
4752 p = find_process_by_pid(pid);
4753 if (!p)
4754 goto out_unlock;
4755
4756 retval = security_task_getscheduler(p);
4757 if (retval)

4759
4760 raw_spin_lock_irqsave(&p->pi_lock, flags);
4761 cpumask_and(mask, &p->cpus_allowed, cpu_active_mask);

4764out_unlock:

4770/**
4771 * sys_sched_getaffinity - get the CPU affinity of a process
4772 * @pid: pid of the process
4773 * @len: length in bytes of the bitmask pointed to by user_mask_ptr
4774 * @user_mask_ptr: user-space pointer to hold the current CPU mask
4775 *
4776 * Return: size of CPU mask copied to user_mask_ptr on success. An
4777 * error code otherwise.
4778 */
4779SYSCALL_DEFINE3(sched_getaffinity, pid_t, pid, unsigned int, len,
4780 unsigned long __user *, user_mask_ptr)
4781{
4782 int ret;
4783 cpumask_var_t mask;
4784
4785 if ((len * BITS_PER_BYTE) < nr_cpu_ids)
4786 return -EINVAL;
4787 if (len & (sizeof(unsigned long)-1))
4788 return -EINVAL;
4789
4790 if (!alloc_cpumask_var(&mask, GFP_KERNEL))
4791 return -ENOMEM;
4792

4794 if (ret == 0) {

4796
4797 if (copy_to_user(user_mask_ptr, mask, retlen))
4798 ret = -EFAULT;
4799 else
4800 ret = retlen;
4801 }
4802 free_cpumask_var(mask);
4803
4804 return ret;
4805}

4807/**
4808 * sys_sched_yield - yield the current processor to other threads.
4809 *
4810 * This function yields the current CPU to other tasks. If there are no
4811 * other threads running on this CPU then this function will return.
4812 *
4813 * Return: 0.
4814 */
4815SYSCALL_DEFINE0(sched_yield)
4816{
4817 struct rq_flags rf;
4818 struct rq *rq;
4819
4820 local_irq_disable();
4821 rq = this_rq();
4822 rq_lock(rq, &rf);
4823
4824 schedstat_inc(rq->yld_count);
4825 current->sched_class->yield_task(rq);
4826
4827 /*
4828 * Since we are going to call schedule() anyway, there's
4829 * no need to preempt or enable interrupts:
4830 */
4831 preempt_disable();
4832 rq_unlock(rq, &rf);
4833 sched_preempt_enable_no_resched();
4834
4835 schedule();
4836
4837 return 0;
4838}

4840#ifndef CONFIG_PREEMPT
4841int __sched _cond_resched(void)
4842{
4843 if (should_resched(0)) {
4844 preempt_schedule_common();
4845 return 1;
4846 }
4847 return 0;
4848}
4849EXPORT_SYMBOL(_cond_resched);
4850#endif

4852/*
4853 * __cond_resched_lock() - if a reschedule is pending, drop the given lock,
4854 * call schedule, and on return reacquire the lock.
4855 *
4856 * This works OK both with and without CONFIG_PREEMPT. We do strange low-level
4857 * operations here to prevent schedule() from being called twice (once via
4858 * spin_unlock(), once by hand).
4859 */
4860int __cond_resched_lock(spinlock_t *lock)
4861{
4862 int resched = should_resched(PREEMPT_LOCK_OFFSET);
4863 int ret = 0;
4864
4865 lockdep_assert_held(lock);
4866
4867 if (spin_needbreak(lock) || resched) {
4868 spin_unlock(lock);
4869 if (resched)
4870 preempt_schedule_common();
4871 else
4872 cpu_relax();
4873 ret = 1;
4874 spin_lock(lock);
4875 }
4876 return ret;
4877}
4878EXPORT_SYMBOL(__cond_resched_lock);

4880int __sched __cond_resched_softirq(void)
4881{
4882 BUG_ON(!in_softirq());
4883
4884 if (should_resched(SOFTIRQ_DISABLE_OFFSET)) {
4885 local_bh_enable();
4886 preempt_schedule_common();
4887 local_bh_disable();
4888 return 1;
4889 }
4890 return 0;
4891}
4892EXPORT_SYMBOL(__cond_resched_softirq);

4894/**
4895 * yield - yield the current processor to other threads.
4896 *
4897 * Do not ever use this function, there's a 99% chance you're doing it wrong.
4898 *
4899 * The scheduler is at all times free to pick the calling task as the most
4900 * eligible task to run, if removing the yield() call from your code breaks
4901 * it, its already broken.
4902 *
4903 * Typical broken usage is:
4904 *
4905 * while (!event)
4906 * yield();
4907 *
4908 * where one assumes that yield() will let 'the other' process run that will
4909 * make event true. If the current task is a SCHED_FIFO task that will never
4910 * happen. Never use yield() as a progress guarantee!!
4911 *
4912 * If you want to use yield() to wait for something, use wait_event().
4913 * If you want to use yield() to be 'nice' for others, use cond_resched().
4914 * If you still want to use yield(), do not!
4915 */
4916void __sched yield(void)
4917{
4918 set_current_state(TASK_RUNNING);
4919 sys_sched_yield();
4920}
4921EXPORT_SYMBOL(yield);
4922
4923/**
4924 * yield_to - yield the current processor to another thread in
4925 * your thread group, or accelerate that thread toward the
4926 * processor it's on.
4927 * @p: target task
4928 * @preempt: whether task preemption is allowed or not
4929 *
4930 * It's the caller's job to ensure that the target task struct
4931 * can't go away on us before we can do any checks.
4932 *
4933 * Return:
4934 * true (>0) if we indeed boosted the target task.
4935 * false (0) if we failed to boost the target.
4936 * -ESRCH if there's no task to yield to.
4937 */
4938int __sched yield_to(struct task_struct *p, bool preempt)
4939{
4940 struct task_struct *curr = current;
4941 struct rq *rq, *p_rq;
4942 unsigned long flags;
4943 int yielded = 0;
4944
4945 local_irq_save(flags);
4946 rq = this_rq();
4947
4948again:
4949 p_rq = task_rq(p);
4950 /*
4951 * If we're the only runnable task on the rq and target rq also
4952 * has only one task, there's absolutely no point in yielding.
4953 */
4954 if (rq->nr_running == 1 && p_rq->nr_running == 1) {
4955 yielded = -ESRCH;
4956 goto out_irq;
4957 }
4958
4959 double_rq_lock(rq, p_rq);
4960 if (task_rq(p) != p_rq) {
4961 double_rq_unlock(rq, p_rq);
4962 goto again;
4963 }
4964
4965 if (!curr->sched_class->yield_to_task)
4966 goto out_unlock;
4967
4968 if (curr->sched_class != p->sched_class)
4969 goto out_unlock;
4970
4971 if (task_running(p_rq, p) || p->state)
4972 goto out_unlock;
4973
4974 yielded = curr->sched_class->yield_to_task(rq, p, preempt);
4975 if (yielded) {
4976 schedstat_inc(rq->yld_count);
4977 /*
4978 * Make p's CPU reschedule; pick_next_entity takes care of
4979 * fairness.
4980 */
4981 if (preempt && rq != p_rq)
4982 resched_curr(p_rq);
4983 }
4984
4985out_unlock:
4986 double_rq_unlock(rq, p_rq);
4987out_irq:
4988 local_irq_restore(flags);
4989
4990 if (yielded > 0)
4991 schedule();
4992
4993 return yielded;
4994}

5092/**
5093 * sys_sched_rr_get_interval - return the default timeslice of a process.
5094 * @pid: pid of the process.
5095 * @interval: userspace pointer to the timeslice value.
5096 *
5097 * this syscall writes the default timeslice value of a given process
5098 * into the user-space timespec buffer. A value of '0' means infinity.
5099 *
5100 * Return: On success, 0 and the timeslice is in @interval. Otherwise,
5101 * an error code.
5102 */
5103SYSCALL_DEFINE2(sched_rr_get_interval, pid_t, pid,
5104 struct timespec __user *, interval)
5105{
5106 struct task_struct *p;
5107 unsigned int time_slice;
5108 struct rq_flags rf;
5109 struct timespec t;
5110 struct rq *rq;
5111 int retval;
5112
5113 if (pid < 0)
5114 return -EINVAL;
5115
5116 retval = -ESRCH;
5117 rcu_read_lock();
5118 p = find_process_by_pid(pid);
5119 if (!p)
5120 goto out_unlock;
5121
5122 retval = security_task_getscheduler(p);
5123 if (retval)
5124 goto out_unlock;
5125
5126 rq = task_rq_lock(p, &rf);
5127 time_slice = 0;
5128 if (p->sched_class->get_rr_interval)
5129 time_slice = p->sched_class->get_rr_interval(rq, p);
5130 task_rq_unlock(rq, p, &rf);
5131
5132 rcu_read_unlock();
5133 jiffies_to_timespec(time_slice, &t);
5134 retval = copy_to_user(interval, &t, sizeof(t)) ? -EFAULT : 0;
5135 return retval;
5136
5137out_unlock:
5138 rcu_read_unlock();
5139 return retval;
5140}

5171static inline bool
5172state_filter_match(unsigned long state_filter, struct task_struct *p)
5173{
5174 /* no filter, everything matches */
5175 if (!state_filter)
5176 return true;
5177
5178 /* filter, but doesn't match */
5179 if (!(p->state & state_filter))
5180 return false;
5181
5182 /*
5183 * When looking for TASK_UNINTERRUPTIBLE skip TASK_IDLE (allows
5184 * TASK_KILLABLE).
5185 */
5186 if (state_filter == TASK_UNINTERRUPTIBLE && p->state == TASK_IDLE)
5187 return false;
5188
5189 return true;
5190}

5231/**
5232 * init_idle - set up an idle thread for a given CPU
5233 * @idle: task in question
5234 * @cpu: CPU the idle task belongs to
5235 *
5236 * NOTE: this function does not set the idle thread's NEED_RESCHED
5237 * flag, to make booting more robust.
5238 */
5239void init_idle(struct task_struct *idle, int cpu)
5240{
5241 struct rq *rq = cpu_rq(cpu);
5242 unsigned long flags;
5243
5244 raw_spin_lock_irqsave(&idle->pi_lock, flags);
5245 raw_spin_lock(&rq->lock);
5246
5247 __sched_fork(0, idle);
5248 idle->state = TASK_RUNNING;
5249 idle->se.exec_start = sched_clock();
5250 idle->flags |= PF_IDLE;
5251
5252 kasan_unpoison_task_stack(idle);
5253
5254#ifdef CONFIG_SMP
5255 /*
5256 * Its possible that init_idle() gets called multiple times on a task,
5257 * in that case do_set_cpus_allowed() will not do the right thing.
5258 *
5259 * And since this is boot we can forgo the serialization.
5260 */
5261 set_cpus_allowed_common(idle, cpumask_of(cpu));
5262#endif
5263 /*
5264 * We're having a chicken and egg problem, even though we are
5265 * holding rq->lock, the CPU isn't yet set to this CPU so the
5266 * lockdep check in task_group() will fail.
5267 *
5268 * Similar case to sched_fork(). / Alternatively we could
5269 * use task_rq_lock() here and obtain the other rq->lock.
5270 *
5271 * Silence PROVE_RCU
5272 */
5273 rcu_read_lock();
5274 __set_task_cpu(idle, cpu);
5275 rcu_read_unlock();
5276
5277 rq->curr = rq->idle = idle;
5278 idle->on_rq = TASK_ON_RQ_QUEUED;
5279#ifdef CONFIG_SMP
5280 idle->on_cpu = 1;
5281#endif
5282 raw_spin_unlock(&rq->lock);
5283 raw_spin_unlock_irqrestore(&idle->pi_lock, flags);
5284
5285 /* Set the preempt count _outside_ the spinlocks! */
5286 init_idle_preempt_count(idle, cpu);
5287
5288 /*
5289 * The idle tasks have their own, simple scheduling class:
5290 */
5291 idle->sched_class = &idle_sched_class;
5292 ftrace_graph_init_idle_task(idle, cpu);
5293 vtime_init_idle(idle, cpu);
5294#ifdef CONFIG_SMP
5295 sprintf(idle->comm, "%s/%d", INIT_TASK_COMM, cpu);
5296#endif
5297}

5313
5314int task_can_attach(struct task_struct *p,
5315 const struct cpumask *cs_cpus_allowed)
5316{
5317 int ret = 0;
5318
5319 /*
5320 * Kthreads which disallow setaffinity shouldn't be moved
5321 * to a new cpuset; we don't want to change their CPU
5322 * affinity and isolating such threads by their set of
5323 * allowed nodes is unnecessary. Thus, cpusets are not
5324 * applicable for such threads. This prevents checking for
5325 * success of set_cpus_allowed_ptr() on all attached tasks
5326 * before cpus_allowed may be changed.
5327 */
5328 if (p->flags & PF_NO_SETAFFINITY) {
5329 ret = -EINVAL;
5330 goto out;
5331 }
5332
5333 if (dl_task(p) && !cpumask_intersects(task_rq(p)->rd->span,
5334 cs_cpus_allowed))
5335 ret = dl_task_can_attach(p, cs_cpus_allowed);
5336
5337out:
5338 return ret;
5339}

5362/*
5363 * Requeue a task on a given node and accurately track the number of NUMA
5364 * tasks on the runqueues
5365 */
5366void sched_setnuma(struct task_struct *p, int nid)
5367{
5368 bool queued, running;
5369 struct rq_flags rf;
5370 struct rq *rq;
5371
5372 rq = task_rq_lock(p, &rf);
5373 queued = task_on_rq_queued(p);
5374 running = task_current(rq, p);
5375
5376 if (queued)
5377 dequeue_task(rq, p, DEQUEUE_SAVE);
5378 if (running)
5379 put_prev_task(rq, p);
5380
5381 p->numa_preferred_nid = nid;
5382
5383 if (queued)
5384 enqueue_task(rq, p, ENQUEUE_RESTORE | ENQUEUE_NOCLOCK);
5385 if (running)
5386 set_curr_task(rq, p);
5387 task_rq_unlock(rq, p, &rf);

5409/*
5410 * Since this CPU is going 'away' for a while, fold any nr_active delta
5411 * we might have. Assumes we're called after migrate_tasks() so that the
5412 * nr_active count is stable. We need to take the teardown thread which
5413 * is calling this into account, so we hand in adjust = 1 to the load
5414 * calculation.
5415 *
5416 * Also see the comment "Global load-average calculations".
5417 */
5418static void calc_load_migrate(struct rq *rq)
5419{
5420 long delta = calc_load_fold_active(rq, 1);
5421 if (delta)
5422 atomic_long_add(delta, &calc_load_tasks);
5423}
5424
5425static void put_prev_task_fake(struct rq *rq, struct task_struct *prev)
5426{
5427}
5428
5429static const struct sched_class fake_sched_class = {
5430 .put_prev_task = put_prev_task_fake,
5431};
5432
5433static struct task_struct fake_task = {
5434 /*
5435 * Avoid pull_{rt,dl}_task()
5436 */
5437 .prio = MAX_PRIO + 1,
5438 .sched_class = &fake_sched_class,
5439};
5440
5441/*
5442 * Migrate all tasks from the rq, sleeping tasks will be migrated by
5443 * try_to_wake_up()->select_task_rq().
5444 *
5445 * Called with rq->lock held even though we'er in stop_machine() and
5446 * there's no concurrency possible, we hold the required locks anyway
5447 * because of lock validation efforts.
5448 */
5449static void migrate_tasks(struct rq *dead_rq, struct rq_flags *rf)
5450{
5451 struct rq *rq = dead_rq;
5452 struct task_struct *next, *stop = rq->stop;
5453 struct rq_flags orf = *rf;
5454 int dest_cpu;
5455
5456 /*
5457 * Fudge the rq selection such that the below task selection loop
5458 * doesn't get stuck on the currently eligible stop task.
5459 *
5460 * We're currently inside stop_machine() and the rq is either stuck
5461 * in the stop_machine_cpu_stop() loop, or we're executing this code,
5462 * either way we should never end up calling schedule() until we're
5463 * done here.
5464 */
5465 rq->stop = NULL;
5466
5467 /*
5468 * put_prev_task() and pick_next_task() sched
5469 * class method both need to have an up-to-date
5470 * value of rq->clock[_task]
5471 */
5472 update_rq_clock(rq);
5473
5474 for (;;) {
5475 /*
5476 * There's this thread running, bail when that's the only
5477 * remaining thread:
5478 */
5479 if (rq->nr_running == 1)
5480 break;
5481
5482 /*
5483 * pick_next_task() assumes pinned rq->lock:
5484 */
5485 next = pick_next_task(rq, &fake_task, rf);
5486 BUG_ON(!next);
5487 put_prev_task(rq, next);
5488
5489 /*
5490 * Rules for changing task_struct::cpus_allowed are holding
5491 * both pi_lock and rq->lock, such that holding either
5492 * stabilizes the mask.
5493 *
5494 * Drop rq->lock is not quite as disastrous as it usually is
5495 * because !cpu_active at this point, which means load-balance
5496 * will not interfere. Also, stop-machine.
5497 */
5498 rq_unlock(rq, rf);
5499 raw_spin_lock(&next->pi_lock);
5500 rq_relock(rq, rf);
5501
5502 /*
5503 * Since we're inside stop-machine, _nothing_ should have
5504 * changed the task, WARN if weird stuff happened, because in
5505 * that case the above rq->lock drop is a fail too.
5506 */
5507 if (WARN_ON(task_rq(next) != rq || !task_on_rq_queued(next))) {
5508 raw_spin_unlock(&next->pi_lock);
5509 continue;
5510 }
5511
5512 /* Find suitable destination for @next, with force if needed. */
5513 dest_cpu = select_fallback_rq(dead_rq->cpu, next);
5514 rq = __migrate_task(rq, rf, next, dest_cpu);
5515 if (rq != dead_rq) {
5516 rq_unlock(rq, rf);
5517 rq = dead_rq;
5518 *rf = orf;
5519 rq_relock(rq, rf);
5520 }
5521 raw_spin_unlock(&next->pi_lock);
5522 }
5523
5524 rq->stop = stop;
5525}
5526#endif /* CONFIG_HOTPLUG_CPU */

5565/*
5566 * used to mark begin/end of suspend/resume:
5567 */
5568static int num_cpus_frozen;
5569
5570/*
5571 * Update cpusets according to cpu_active mask. If cpusets are
5572 * disabled, cpuset_update_active_cpus() becomes a simple wrapper
5573 * around partition_sched_domains().
5574 *
5575 * If we come here as part of a suspend/resume, don't touch cpusets because we
5576 * want to restore it back to its original state upon resume anyway.
5577 */
5578static void cpuset_cpu_active(void)
5579{
5580 if (cpuhp_tasks_frozen) {
5581 /*
5582 * num_cpus_frozen tracks how many CPUs are involved in suspend
5583 * resume sequence. As long as this is not the last online
5584 * operation in the resume sequence, just build a single sched
5585 * domain, ignoring cpusets.
5586 */
5587 partition_sched_domains(1, NULL, NULL);
5588 if (--num_cpus_frozen)
5589 return;
5590 /*
5591 * This is the last CPU online operation. So fall through and
5592 * restore the original sched domains by considering the
5593 * cpuset configurations.
5594 */
5595 cpuset_force_rebuild();
5596 }
5597 cpuset_update_active_cpus();
5598}
5599
5600static int cpuset_cpu_inactive(unsigned int cpu)
5601{
5602 if (!cpuhp_tasks_frozen) {
5603 if (dl_cpu_busy(cpu))
5604 return -EBUSY;
5605 cpuset_update_active_cpus();
5606 } else {
5607 num_cpus_frozen++;
5608 partition_sched_domains(1, NULL, NULL);
5609 }
5610 return 0;
5611}

5613int sched_cpu_activate(unsigned int cpu)
5614{
5615 struct rq *rq = cpu_rq(cpu);
5616 struct rq_flags rf;
5617
5618 set_cpu_active(cpu, true);
5619
5620 if (sched_smp_initialized) {
5621 sched_domains_numa_masks_set(cpu);
5622 cpuset_cpu_active();
5623 }
5624
5625 /*
5626 * Put the rq online, if not already. This happens:
5627 *
5628 * 1) In the early boot process, because we build the real domains
5629 * after all CPUs have been brought up.
5630 *
5631 * 2) At runtime, if cpuset_cpu_active() fails to rebuild the
5632 * domains.
5633 */
5634 rq_lock_irqsave(rq, &rf);
5635 if (rq->rd) {
5636 BUG_ON(!cpumask_test_cpu(cpu, rq->rd->span));
5637 set_rq_online(rq);
5638 }
5639 rq_unlock_irqrestore(rq, &rf);
5640
5641 update_max_interval();
5642
5643 return 0;
5644}
5645
5646int sched_cpu_deactivate(unsigned int cpu)
5647{
5648 int ret;
5649
5650 set_cpu_active(cpu, false);
5651 /*
5652 * We've cleared cpu_active_mask, wait for all preempt-disabled and RCU
5653 * users of this state to go away such that all new such users will
5654 * observe it.
5655 *
5656 * Do sync before park smpboot threads to take care the rcu boost case.
5657 */
5658 synchronize_rcu_mult(call_rcu, call_rcu_sched);
5659
5660 if (!sched_smp_initialized)
5661 return 0;
5662
5663 ret = cpuset_cpu_inactive(cpu);
5664 if (ret) {
5665 set_cpu_active(cpu, true);
5666 return ret;
5667 }
5668 sched_domains_numa_masks_clear(cpu);
5669 return 0;
5670}

5688int sched_cpu_dying(unsigned int cpu)
5689{

5729void __init sched_init_smp(void)
5730{
5731 cpumask_var_t non_isolated_cpus;
5732
5733 alloc_cpumask_var(&non_isolated_cpus, GFP_KERNEL);
5734
5735 sched_init_numa();
5736
5737 /*
5738 * There's no userspace yet to cause hotplug operations; hence all the
5739 * CPU masks are stable and all blatant races in the below code cannot
5740 * happen.
5741 */
5742 mutex_lock(&sched_domains_mutex);
5743 sched_init_domains(cpu_active_mask);
5744 cpumask_andnot(non_isolated_cpus, cpu_possible_mask, cpu_isolated_map);
5745 if (cpumask_empty(non_isolated_cpus))
5746 cpumask_set_cpu(smp_processor_id(), non_isolated_cpus);
5747 mutex_unlock(&sched_domains_mutex);
5748
5749 /* Move init over to a non-isolated CPU */
5750 if (set_cpus_allowed_ptr(current, non_isolated_cpus) < 0)
5751 BUG();
5752 sched_init_granularity();
5753 free_cpumask_var(non_isolated_cpus);
5754
5755 init_sched_rt_class();
5756 init_sched_dl_class();
5757
5758 sched_init_smt();
5759
5760 sched_smp_initialized = true;
5761}

5764{
5765 sched_rq_cpu_starting(smp_processor_id());
5766 return 0;
5767}
5768early_initcall(migration_init);
5769
5770#else
5771void __init sched_init_smp(void)
5772{
5773 sched_init_granularity();
5774}
5775#endif /* CONFIG_SMP */

5779 return in_lock_functions(addr) ||
5780 (addr >= (unsigned long)__sched_text_start
5781 && addr < (unsigned long)__sched_text_end);

5784#ifdef CONFIG_CGROUP_SCHED
5785/*
5786 * Default task group.
5787 * Every task in system belongs to this group at bootup.
5788 */
5789struct task_group root_task_group;
5790LIST_HEAD(task_groups);

5792/* Cacheline aligned slab cache for task_group */
5793static struct kmem_cache *task_group_cache __read_mostly;

5795
5796DECLARE_PER_CPU(cpumask_var_t, load_balance_mask);
5797DECLARE_PER_CPU(cpumask_var_t, select_idle_mask);
5798
5799void __init sched_init(void)
5800{
5801 int i, j;
5802 unsigned long alloc_size = 0, ptr;
5803
5804 sched_clock_init();
5805 wait_bit_init();
5806
5807#ifdef CONFIG_FAIR_GROUP_SCHED
5808 alloc_size += 2 * nr_cpu_ids * sizeof(void **);
5809#endif
5810#ifdef CONFIG_RT_GROUP_SCHED
5811 alloc_size += 2 * nr_cpu_ids * sizeof(void **);
5812#endif
5813 if (alloc_size) {
5814 ptr = (unsigned long)kzalloc(alloc_size, GFP_NOWAIT);
5815
5816#ifdef CONFIG_FAIR_GROUP_SCHED
5817 root_task_group.se = (struct sched_entity **)ptr;
5818 ptr += nr_cpu_ids * sizeof(void **);
5819
5820 root_task_group.cfs_rq = (struct cfs_rq **)ptr;
5821 ptr += nr_cpu_ids * sizeof(void **);
5822
5823#endif /* CONFIG_FAIR_GROUP_SCHED */
5824#ifdef CONFIG_RT_GROUP_SCHED
5825 root_task_group.rt_se = (struct sched_rt_entity **)ptr;
5826 ptr += nr_cpu_ids * sizeof(void **);
5827
5828 root_task_group.rt_rq = (struct rt_rq **)ptr;
5829 ptr += nr_cpu_ids * sizeof(void **);
5830
5831#endif /* CONFIG_RT_GROUP_SCHED */
5832 }
5833#ifdef CONFIG_CPUMASK_OFFSTACK
5834 for_each_possible_cpu(i) {
5835 per_cpu(load_balance_mask, i) = (cpumask_var_t)kzalloc_node(
5836 cpumask_size(), GFP_KERNEL, cpu_to_node(i));
5837 per_cpu(select_idle_mask, i) = (cpumask_var_t)kzalloc_node(
5838 cpumask_size(), GFP_KERNEL, cpu_to_node(i));
5839 }
5840#endif /* CONFIG_CPUMASK_OFFSTACK */
5841
5842 init_rt_bandwidth(&def_rt_bandwidth, global_rt_period(), global_rt_runtime());
5843 init_dl_bandwidth(&def_dl_bandwidth, global_rt_period(), global_rt_runtime());
5844
5845#ifdef CONFIG_SMP
5846 init_defrootdomain();
5847#endif
5848
5849#ifdef CONFIG_RT_GROUP_SCHED
5850 init_rt_bandwidth(&root_task_group.rt_bandwidth,
5851 global_rt_period(), global_rt_runtime());
5852#endif /* CONFIG_RT_GROUP_SCHED */
5853
5854#ifdef CONFIG_CGROUP_SCHED
5855 task_group_cache = KMEM_CACHE(task_group, 0);
5856
5857 list_add(&root_task_group.list, &task_groups);
5858 INIT_LIST_HEAD(&root_task_group.children);
5859 INIT_LIST_HEAD(&root_task_group.siblings);
5860 autogroup_init(&init_task);
5861#endif /* CONFIG_CGROUP_SCHED */
5862
5863 for_each_possible_cpu(i) {
5864 struct rq *rq;
5865
5866 rq = cpu_rq(i);
5867 raw_spin_lock_init(&rq->lock);
5868 rq->nr_running = 0;
5869 rq->calc_load_active = 0;
5870 rq->calc_load_update = jiffies + LOAD_FREQ;
5871 init_cfs_rq(&rq->cfs);
5872 init_rt_rq(&rq->rt);
5873 init_dl_rq(&rq->dl);
5874#ifdef CONFIG_FAIR_GROUP_SCHED
5875 root_task_group.shares = ROOT_TASK_GROUP_LOAD;
5876 INIT_LIST_HEAD(&rq->leaf_cfs_rq_list);
5877 rq->tmp_alone_branch = &rq->leaf_cfs_rq_list;
5878 /*
5879 * How much CPU bandwidth does root_task_group get?
5880 *
5881 * In case of task-groups formed thr' the cgroup filesystem, it
5882 * gets 100% of the CPU resources in the system. This overall
5883 * system CPU resource is divided among the tasks of
5884 * root_task_group and its child task-groups in a fair manner,
5885 * based on each entity's (task or task-group's) weight
5886 * (se->load.weight).
5887 *
5888 * In other words, if root_task_group has 10 tasks of weight
5889 * 1024) and two child groups A0 and A1 (of weight 1024 each),
5890 * then A0's share of the CPU resource is:
5891 *
5892 * A0's bandwidth = 1024 / (10*1024 + 1024 + 1024) = 8.33%
5893 *
5894 * We achieve this by letting root_task_group's tasks sit
5895 * directly in rq->cfs (i.e root_task_group->se[] = NULL).
5896 */
5897 init_cfs_bandwidth(&root_task_group.cfs_bandwidth);
5898 init_tg_cfs_entry(&root_task_group, &rq->cfs, NULL, i, NULL);
5899#endif /* CONFIG_FAIR_GROUP_SCHED */
5900
5901 rq->rt.rt_runtime = def_rt_bandwidth.rt_runtime;
5902#ifdef CONFIG_RT_GROUP_SCHED
5903 init_tg_rt_entry(&root_task_group, &rq->rt, NULL, i, NULL);
5904#endif
5905
5906 for (j = 0; j < CPU_LOAD_IDX_MAX; j++)
5907 rq->cpu_load[j] = 0;
5908
5909#ifdef CONFIG_SMP
5910 rq->sd = NULL;
5911 rq->rd = NULL;
5912 rq->cpu_capacity = rq->cpu_capacity_orig = SCHED_CAPACITY_SCALE;
5913 rq->balance_callback = NULL;
5914 rq->active_balance = 0;
5915 rq->next_balance = jiffies;
5916 rq->push_cpu = 0;
5917 rq->cpu = i;
5918 rq->online = 0;
5919 rq->idle_stamp = 0;
5920 rq->avg_idle = 2*sysctl_sched_migration_cost;
5921 rq->max_idle_balance_cost = sysctl_sched_migration_cost;
5922
5923 INIT_LIST_HEAD(&rq->cfs_tasks);
5924
5925 rq_attach_root(rq, &def_root_domain);
5926#ifdef CONFIG_NO_HZ_COMMON
5927 rq->last_load_update_tick = jiffies;
5928 rq->nohz_flags = 0;
5929#endif
5930#ifdef CONFIG_NO_HZ_FULL
5931 rq->last_sched_tick = 0;
5932#endif
5933#endif /* CONFIG_SMP */
5934 init_rq_hrtick(rq);
5935 atomic_set(&rq->nr_iowait, 0);
5936 }
5937
5938 set_load_weight(&init_task);
5939
5940 /*
5941 * The boot idle thread does lazy MMU switching as well:
5942 */
5943 mmgrab(&init_mm);
5944 enter_lazy_tlb(&init_mm, current);
5945
5946 /*
5947 * Make us the idle thread. Technically, schedule() should not be
5948 * called from this thread, however somewhere below it might be,
5949 * but because we are the idle thread, we just pick up running again
5950 * when this runqueue becomes "idle".
5951 */
5952 init_idle(current, smp_processor_id());
5953
5954 calc_load_update = jiffies + LOAD_FREQ;
5955
5956#ifdef CONFIG_SMP
5957 /* May be allocated at isolcpus cmdline parse time */
5958 if (cpu_isolated_map == NULL)
5959 zalloc_cpumask_var(&cpu_isolated_map, GFP_NOWAIT);
5960 idle_thread_set_boot_cpu();
5961 set_cpu_rq_start_time(smp_processor_id());
5962#endif
5963 init_sched_fair_class();
5964
5965 init_schedstats();
5966
5967 scheduler_running = 1;
5968}

5970#ifdef CONFIG_DEBUG_ATOMIC_SLEEP
5971static inline int preempt_count_equals(int preempt_offset)
5972{
5973 int nested = preempt_count() + rcu_preempt_depth();
5974
5975 return (nested == preempt_offset);

5977
5978void __might_sleep(const char *file, int line, int preempt_offset)
5979{
5980 /*
5981 * Blocking primitives will set (and therefore destroy) current->state,
5982 * since we will exit with TASK_RUNNING make sure we enter with it,
5983 * otherwise we will destroy state.
5984 */
5985 WARN_ONCE(current->state != TASK_RUNNING && current->task_state_change,
5986 "do not call blocking ops when !TASK_RUNNING; "
5987 "state=%lx set at [<%p>] %pS\n",
5988 current->state,
5989 (void *)current->task_state_change,
5990 (void *)current->task_state_change);
5991
5992 ___might_sleep(file, line, preempt_offset);
5993}
5994EXPORT_SYMBOL(__might_sleep);
5995
5996void ___might_sleep(const char *file, int line, int preempt_offset)
5997{
5998 /* Ratelimiting timestamp: */
5999 static unsigned long prev_jiffy;
6000
6001 unsigned long preempt_disable_ip;
6002
6003 /* WARN_ON_ONCE() by default, no rate limit required: */
6004 rcu_sleep_check();
6005
6006 if ((preempt_count_equals(preempt_offset) && !irqs_disabled() &&
6007 !is_idle_task(current)) ||
6008 system_state == SYSTEM_BOOTING || system_state > SYSTEM_RUNNING ||
6009 oops_in_progress)
6010 return;
6011
6012 if (time_before(jiffies, prev_jiffy + HZ) && prev_jiffy)
6013 return;
6014 prev_jiffy = jiffies;
6015
6016 /* Save this before calling printk(), since that will clobber it: */
6017 preempt_disable_ip = get_preempt_disable_ip(current);
6018
6019 printk(KERN_ERR
6020 "BUG: sleeping function called from invalid context at %s:%d\n",
6021 file, line);
6022 printk(KERN_ERR
6023 "in_atomic(): %d, irqs_disabled(): %d, pid: %d, name: %s\n",
6024 in_atomic(), irqs_disabled(),
6025 current->pid, current->comm);
6026
6027 if (task_stack_end_corrupted(current))
6028 printk(KERN_EMERG "Thread overran stack, or stack corrupted\n");
6029
6030 debug_show_held_locks(current);
6031 if (irqs_disabled())
6032 print_irqtrace_events(current);
6033 if (IS_ENABLED(CONFIG_DEBUG_PREEMPT)
6034 && !preempt_count_equals(preempt_offset)) {
6035 pr_err("Preemption disabled at:");
6036 print_ip_sym(preempt_disable_ip);
6037 pr_cont("\n");
6038 }
6039 dump_stack();
6040 add_taint(TAINT_WARN, LOCKDEP_STILL_OK);
6041}
6042EXPORT_SYMBOL(___might_sleep);
6043#endif

6045#ifdef CONFIG_MAGIC_SYSRQ
6046void normalize_rt_tasks(void)
6047{
6048 struct task_struct *g, *p;
6049 struct sched_attr attr = {
6050 .sched_policy = SCHED_NORMAL,
6051 };
6052
6053 read_lock(&tasklist_lock);
6054 for_each_process_thread(g, p) {
6055 /*
6056 * Only normalize user tasks:
6057 */
6058 if (p->flags & PF_KTHREAD)
6059 continue;
6060
6061 p->se.exec_start = 0;
6062 schedstat_set(p->se.statistics.wait_start, 0);
6063 schedstat_set(p->se.statistics.sleep_start, 0);
6064 schedstat_set(p->se.statistics.block_start, 0);
6065
6066 if (!dl_task(p) && !rt_task(p)) {
6067 /*
6068 * Renice negative nice level userspace
6069 * tasks back to 0:
6070 */
6071 if (task_nice(p) < 0)
6072 set_user_nice(p, 0);
6073 continue;
6074 }
6075
6076 __sched_setscheduler(p, &attr, false, false);
6077 }
6078 read_unlock(&tasklist_lock);
6079}

6081#endif /* CONFIG_MAGIC_SYSRQ */

6083#if defined(CONFIG_IA64) || defined(CONFIG_KGDB_KDB)
6084/*
6085 * These functions are only useful for the IA64 MCA handling, or kdb.
6086 *
6087 * They can only be called when the whole system has been
6088 * stopped - every CPU needs to be quiescent, and no scheduling
6089 * activity can take place. Using them for anything else would

6096 * @cpu: the processor in question.
6097 *
6098 * ONLY VALID WHEN THE WHOLE SYSTEM IS STOPPED!
6099 *
6100 * Return: The current task for @cpu.
6101 */
6102struct task_struct *curr_task(int cpu)
6103{
6104 return cpu_curr(cpu);
6105}
6106
6107#endif /* defined(CONFIG_IA64) || defined(CONFIG_KGDB_KDB) */

6109#ifdef CONFIG_IA64
6110/**
6111 * set_curr_task - set the current task for a given CPU.
6112 * @cpu: the processor in question.
6113 * @p: the task pointer to set.
6114 *
6115 * Description: This function must only be used when non-maskable interrupts
6116 * are serviced on a separate stack. It allows the architecture to switch the
6117 * notion of the current task on a CPU in a non-blocking manner. This function
6118 * must be called with all CPU's synchronized, and interrupts disabled, the
6119 * and caller must save the original value of the current task (see
6120 * curr_task() above) and restore that value before reenabling interrupts and
6121 * re-starting the system.
6122 *
6123 * ONLY VALID WHEN THE WHOLE SYSTEM IS STOPPED!
6124 */
6125void ia64_set_curr_task(int cpu, struct task_struct *p)

6132#ifdef CONFIG_CGROUP_SCHED
6133/* task_group_lock serializes the addition/removal of task groups */
6134static DEFINE_SPINLOCK(task_group_lock);
6135
6136static void sched_free_group(struct task_group *tg)
6137{
6138 free_fair_sched_group(tg);
6139 free_rt_sched_group(tg);
6140 autogroup_free(tg);
6141 kmem_cache_free(task_group_cache, tg);
6142}
6143
6144/* allocate runqueue etc for a new task group */
6145struct task_group *sched_create_group(struct task_group *parent)
6146{
6147 struct task_group *tg;
6148
6149 tg = kmem_cache_alloc(task_group_cache, GFP_KERNEL | __GFP_ZERO);
6150 if (!tg)
6151 return ERR_PTR(-ENOMEM);
6152
6153 if (!alloc_fair_sched_group(tg, parent))
6154 goto err;
6155
6156 if (!alloc_rt_sched_group(tg, parent))
6157 goto err;
6158
6159 return tg;
6160
6161err:
6162 sched_free_group(tg);
6163 return ERR_PTR(-ENOMEM);
6164}
6165
6166void sched_online_group(struct task_group *tg, struct task_group *parent)
6167{
6168 unsigned long flags;
6169
6170 spin_lock_irqsave(&task_group_lock, flags);
6171 list_add_rcu(&tg->list, &task_groups);
6172
6173 /* Root should already exist: */
6174 WARN_ON(!parent);
6175
6176 tg->parent = parent;
6177 INIT_LIST_HEAD(&tg->children);
6178 list_add_rcu(&tg->siblings, &parent->children);
6179 spin_unlock_irqrestore(&task_group_lock, flags);
6180
6181 online_fair_sched_group(tg);
6182}
6183
6184/* rcu callback to free various structures associated with a task group */
6185static void sched_free_group_rcu(struct rcu_head *rhp)
6186{
6187 /* Now it should be safe to free those cfs_rqs: */
6188 sched_free_group(container_of(rhp, struct task_group, rcu));
6189}
6190
6191void sched_destroy_group(struct task_group *tg)
6192{
6193 /* Wait for possible concurrent references to cfs_rqs complete: */
6194 call_rcu(&tg->rcu, sched_free_group_rcu);
6195}
6196
6197void sched_offline_group(struct task_group *tg)
6198{
6199 unsigned long flags;
6200
6201 /* End participation in shares distribution: */
6202 unregister_fair_sched_group(tg);
6203
6204 spin_lock_irqsave(&task_group_lock, flags);
6205 list_del_rcu(&tg->list);
6206 list_del_rcu(&tg->siblings);
6207 spin_unlock_irqrestore(&task_group_lock, flags);
6208}

6210static void sched_change_group(struct task_struct *tsk, int type)
6211{
6212 struct task_group *tg;
6213
6214 /*
6215 * All callers are synchronized by task_rq_lock(); we do not use RCU
6216 * which is pointless here. Thus, we pass "true" to task_css_check()
6217 * to prevent lockdep warnings.
6218 */
6219 tg = container_of(task_css_check(tsk, cpu_cgrp_id, true),
6220 struct task_group, css);
6221 tg = autogroup_task_group(tsk, tg);
6222 tsk->sched_task_group = tg;
6223
6224#ifdef CONFIG_FAIR_GROUP_SCHED
6225 if (tsk->sched_class->task_change_group)
6226 tsk->sched_class->task_change_group(tsk, type);
6227 else
6228#endif
6229 set_task_rq(tsk, task_cpu(tsk));
6230}
6231
6232/*
6233 * Change task's runqueue when it moves between groups.
6234 *
6235 * The caller of this function should have put the task in its new group by
6236 * now. This function just updates tsk->se.cfs_rq and tsk->se.parent to reflect
6237 * its new group.
6238 */
6239void sched_move_task(struct task_struct *tsk)
6240{
6241 int queued, running, queue_flags =
6242 DEQUEUE_SAVE | DEQUEUE_MOVE | DEQUEUE_NOCLOCK;
6243 struct rq_flags rf;
6244 struct rq *rq;
6245
6246 rq = task_rq_lock(tsk, &rf);
6247 update_rq_clock(rq);
6248
6249 running = task_current(rq, tsk);
6250 queued = task_on_rq_queued(tsk);
6251
6252 if (queued)
6253 dequeue_task(rq, tsk, queue_flags);
6254 if (running)
6255 put_prev_task(rq, tsk);
6256
6257 sched_change_group(tsk, TASK_MOVE_GROUP);
6258
6259 if (queued)
6260 enqueue_task(rq, tsk, queue_flags);
6261 if (running)
6262 set_curr_task(rq, tsk);
6263
6264 task_rq_unlock(rq, tsk, &rf);
6265}

6267static inline struct task_group *css_tg(struct cgroup_subsys_state *css)
6268{
6269 return css ? container_of(css, struct task_group, css) : NULL;
6270}
6271
6272static struct cgroup_subsys_state *
6273cpu_cgroup_css_alloc(struct cgroup_subsys_state *parent_css)
6274{
6275 struct task_group *parent = css_tg(parent_css);
6276 struct task_group *tg;
6277
6278 if (!parent) {
6279 /* This is early initialization for the top cgroup */
6280 return &root_task_group.css;
6281 }
6282
6283 tg = sched_create_group(parent);
6284 if (IS_ERR(tg))
6285 return ERR_PTR(-ENOMEM);
6286
6287 return &tg->css;
6288}
6289
6290/* Expose task group only after completing cgroup initialization */
6291static int cpu_cgroup_css_online(struct cgroup_subsys_state *css)
6292{
6293 struct task_group *tg = css_tg(css);
6294 struct task_group *parent = css_tg(css->parent);
6295
6296 if (parent)
6297 sched_online_group(tg, parent);
6298 return 0;
6299}

6301static void cpu_cgroup_css_released(struct cgroup_subsys_state *css)
6302{
6303 struct task_group *tg = css_tg(css);
6304
6305 sched_offline_group(tg);
6306}

6308static void cpu_cgroup_css_free(struct cgroup_subsys_state *css)
6309{
6310 struct task_group *tg = css_tg(css);
6311
6312 /*
6313 * Relies on the RCU grace period between css_released() and this.
6314 */
6315 sched_free_group(tg);
6316}

6318/*
6319 * This is called before wake_up_new_task(), therefore we really only
6320 * have to set its group bits, all the other stuff does not apply.
6321 */
6322static void cpu_cgroup_fork(struct task_struct *task)
6323{
6324 struct rq_flags rf;
6325 struct rq *rq;
6326
6327 rq = task_rq_lock(task, &rf);
6328
6329 update_rq_clock(rq);
6330 sched_change_group(task, TASK_SET_GROUP);
6331
6332 task_rq_unlock(rq, task, &rf);
6333}
6334
6335static int cpu_cgroup_can_attach(struct cgroup_taskset *tset)
6336{
6337 struct task_struct *task;
6338 struct cgroup_subsys_state *css;
6339 int ret = 0;
6340
6341 cgroup_taskset_for_each(task, css, tset) {
6342#ifdef CONFIG_RT_GROUP_SCHED
6343 if (!sched_rt_can_attach(css_tg(css), task))
6344 return -EINVAL;
6345#else
6346 /* We don't support RT-tasks being in separate groups */
6347 if (task->sched_class != &fair_sched_class)
6348 return -EINVAL;
6349#endif
6350 /*
6351 * Serialize against wake_up_new_task() such that if its
6352 * running, we're sure to observe its full state.
6353 */
6354 raw_spin_lock_irq(&task->pi_lock);
6355 /*
6356 * Avoid calling sched_move_task() before wake_up_new_task()
6357 * has happened. This would lead to problems with PELT, due to
6358 * move wanting to detach+attach while we're not attached yet.
6359 */
6360 if (task->state == TASK_NEW)
6361 ret = -EINVAL;
6362 raw_spin_unlock_irq(&task->pi_lock);
6363
6364 if (ret)
6365 break;
6366 }
6367 return ret;
6368}
6369
6370static void cpu_cgroup_attach(struct cgroup_taskset *tset)
6371{
6372 struct task_struct *task;
6373 struct cgroup_subsys_state *css;
6374
6375 cgroup_taskset_for_each(task, css, tset)
6376 sched_move_task(task);
6377}

6397const u64 max_cfs_quota_period = 1 * NSEC_PER_SEC; /* 1s */
6398const u64 min_cfs_quota_period = 1 * NSEC_PER_MSEC; /* 1ms */
6399
6400static int __cfs_schedulable(struct task_group *tg, u64 period, u64 runtime);
6401
6402static int tg_set_cfs_bandwidth(struct task_group *tg, u64 period, u64 quota)
6403{
6404 int i, ret = 0, runtime_enabled, runtime_was_enabled;
6405 struct cfs_bandwidth *cfs_b = &tg->cfs_bandwidth;
6406
6407 if (tg == &root_task_group)
6408 return -EINVAL;
6409
6410 /*
6411 * Ensure we have at some amount of bandwidth every period. This is
6412 * to prevent reaching a state of large arrears when throttled via
6413 * entity_tick() resulting in prolonged exit starvation.
6414 */
6415 if (quota < min_cfs_quota_period || period < min_cfs_quota_period)
6416 return -EINVAL;
6417
6418 /*
6419 * Likewise, bound things on the otherside by preventing insane quota
6420 * periods. This also allows us to normalize in computing quota
6421 * feasibility.
6422 */
6423 if (period > max_cfs_quota_period)
6424 return -EINVAL;
6425
6426 /*
6427 * Prevent race between setting of cfs_rq->runtime_enabled and
6428 * unthrottle_offline_cfs_rqs().
6429 */
6430 get_online_cpus();
6431 mutex_lock(&cfs_constraints_mutex);
6432 ret = __cfs_schedulable(tg, period, quota);
6433 if (ret)
6434 goto out_unlock;
6435
6436 runtime_enabled = quota != RUNTIME_INF;
6437 runtime_was_enabled = cfs_b->quota != RUNTIME_INF;
6438 /*
6439 * If we need to toggle cfs_bandwidth_used, off->on must occur
6440 * before making related changes, and on->off must occur afterwards
6441 */
6442 if (runtime_enabled && !runtime_was_enabled)
6443 cfs_bandwidth_usage_inc();
6444 raw_spin_lock_irq(&cfs_b->lock);
6445 cfs_b->period = ns_to_ktime(period);
6446 cfs_b->quota = quota;
6447
6448 __refill_cfs_bandwidth_runtime(cfs_b);
6449
6450 /* Restart the period timer (if active) to handle new period expiry: */
6451 if (runtime_enabled)
6452 start_cfs_bandwidth(cfs_b);
6453
6454 raw_spin_unlock_irq(&cfs_b->lock);
6455
6456 for_each_online_cpu(i) {
6457 struct cfs_rq *cfs_rq = tg->cfs_rq[i];
6458 struct rq *rq = cfs_rq->rq;
6459 struct rq_flags rf;
6460
6461 rq_lock_irq(rq, &rf);
6462 cfs_rq->runtime_enabled = runtime_enabled;
6463 cfs_rq->runtime_remaining = 0;
6464
6465 if (cfs_rq->throttled)
6466 unthrottle_cfs_rq(cfs_rq);
6467 rq_unlock_irq(rq, &rf);
6468 }
6469 if (runtime_was_enabled && !runtime_enabled)
6470 cfs_bandwidth_usage_dec();
6471out_unlock:
6472 mutex_unlock(&cfs_constraints_mutex);
6473 put_online_cpus();
6474
6475 return ret;
6476}

6478int tg_set_cfs_quota(struct task_group *tg, long cfs_quota_us)
6479{
6480 u64 quota, period;
6481
6482 period = ktime_to_ns(tg->cfs_bandwidth.period);
6483 if (cfs_quota_us < 0)
6484 quota = RUNTIME_INF;
6485 else
6486 quota = (u64)cfs_quota_us * NSEC_PER_USEC;
6487
6488 return tg_set_cfs_bandwidth(tg, period, quota);
6489}

6548struct cfs_schedulable_data {
6549 struct task_group *tg;
6550 u64 period, quota;

6553/*
6554 * normalize group quota/period to be quota/max_period
6555 * note: units are usecs
6556 */
6557static u64 normalize_cfs_quota(struct task_group *tg,
6558 struct cfs_schedulable_data *d)
6559{
6560 u64 quota, period;
6561
6562 if (tg == d->tg) {
6563 period = d->period;
6564 quota = d->quota;
6565 } else {
6566 period = tg_get_cfs_period(tg);
6567 quota = tg_get_cfs_quota(tg);
6568 }
6569
6570 /* note: these should typically be equivalent */
6571 if (quota == RUNTIME_INF || quota == -1)
6572 return RUNTIME_INF;
6573
6574 return to_ratio(period, quota);
6575}
6576
6577static int tg_cfs_schedulable_down(struct task_group *tg, void *data)
6578{
6579 struct cfs_schedulable_data *d = data;
6580 struct cfs_bandwidth *cfs_b = &tg->cfs_bandwidth;
6581 s64 quota = 0, parent_quota = -1;
6582
6583 if (!tg->parent) {
6584 quota = RUNTIME_INF;
6585 } else {
6586 struct cfs_bandwidth *parent_b = &tg->parent->cfs_bandwidth;
6587
6588 quota = normalize_cfs_quota(tg, d);
6589 parent_quota = parent_b->hierarchical_quota;
6590
6591 /*
6592 * Ensure max(child_quota) <= parent_quota, inherit when no
6593 * limit is set:
6594 */
6595 if (quota == RUNTIME_INF)
6596 quota = parent_quota;
6597 else if (parent_quota != RUNTIME_INF && quota > parent_quota)
6598 return -EINVAL;
6599 }
6600 cfs_b->hierarchical_quota = quota;
6601
6602 return 0;
6603}
6604
6605static int __cfs_schedulable(struct task_group *tg, u64 period, u64 quota)
6606{
6607 int ret;
6608 struct cfs_schedulable_data data = {
6609 .tg = tg,
6610 .period = period,
6611 .quota = quota,
6612 };
6613
6614 if (quota != RUNTIME_INF) {
6615 do_div(data.period, NSEC_PER_USEC);
6616 do_div(data.quota, NSEC_PER_USEC);
6617 }
6618
6619 rcu_read_lock();
6620 ret = walk_tg_tree(tg_cfs_schedulable_down, tg_nop, &data);
6621 rcu_read_unlock();
6622
6623 return ret;
6624}

6725/*
6726 * Nice levels are multiplicative, with a gentle 10% change for every
6727 * nice level changed. I.e. when a CPU-bound task goes from nice 0 to
6728 * nice 1, it will get ~10% less CPU time than another CPU-bound task
6729 * that remained on nice 0.
6730 *
6731 * The "10% effect" is relative and cumulative: from _any_ nice level,
6732 * if you go up 1 level, it's -10% CPU usage, if you go down 1 level
6733 * it's +10% CPU usage. (to achieve that we use a multiplier of 1.25.
6734 * If a task goes up by ~10% and another task goes down by ~10% then
6735 * the relative distance between them is ~25%.)
6736 */
6737const int sched_prio_to_weight[40] = {
6738 /* -20 */ 88761, 71755, 56483, 46273, 36291,
6739 /* -15 */ 29154, 23254, 18705, 14949, 11916,
6740 /* -10 */ 9548, 7620, 6100, 4904, 3906,
6741 /* -5 */ 3121, 2501, 1991, 1586, 1277,
6742 /* 0 */ 1024, 820, 655, 526, 423,
6743 /* 5 */ 335, 272, 215, 172, 137,
6744 /* 10 */ 110, 87, 70, 56, 45,
6745 /* 15 */ 36, 29, 23, 18, 15,
6746};
6747
6748/*
6749 * Inverse (2^32/x) values of the sched_prio_to_weight[] array, precalculated.
6750 *
6751 * In cases where the weight does not change often, we can use the
6752 * precalculated inverse to speed up arithmetics by turning divisions
6753 * into multiplications:
6754 */
6755const u32 sched_prio_to_wmult[40] = {
6756 /* -20 */ 48388, 59856, 76040, 92818, 118348,
6757 /* -15 */ 147320, 184698, 229616, 287308, 360437,
6758 /* -10 */ 449829, 563644, 704093, 875809, 1099582,
6759 /* -5 */ 1376151, 1717300, 2157191, 2708050, 3363326,
6760 /* 0 */ 4194304, 5237765, 6557202, 8165337, 10153587,
6761 /* 5 */ 12820798, 15790321, 19976592, 24970740, 31350126,
6762 /* 10 */ 39045157, 49367440, 61356676, 76695844, 95443717,
6763 /* 15 */ 119304647, 148102320, 186737708, 238609294, 286331153,
6764};
